Date: 5 Jul 2000
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AFP English 5 Jul 2000 09:59 GMT [edited

Four people in the east Malaysian state of Sarawak have been confirmed to
be infected [sic with the pig-borne Nipah virus that killed 105 people
between 1998 and 1999, officials said Wednesday. State health director Yao
Sik Chi, quoted by the official Bernama news agency, said the 4 were from
the Sibu area. He said that 2 worked at a quarantined pig farm and the
other 2 at an abattoir. They had tested positive for the Nipah virus [sic
in the course of blood tests on 160 people and would be referred to
hospital for further examination.
"At the time when their blood was taken, they were all healthy," he said.
Yao said the department was currently collecting blood samples from farm
workers and family members at eight newly-quarantined pig farms.
David Teng, state public health assistant minister, said that as of Monday
15 pig farms in Sarawak were quarantined pending the result of blood tests
conducted in Australia.
In peninsular Malaysia more than 1700 pigs were slaughtered recently after
some were found to be infected, but there have been no reports of human
infections.
--
