<promed@promedmail.org>
[It does not take great sophistication to recognize that antibody to Nipah
virus is what one wants, it is not a sign of illness, or of current disease
or infectivity. There is a huge difference between "be infected" (the
wording of the report) and "have been infected" (my words). Let me put it
this way: You (the reader of this message) likely have antibody to the
polioviruses, measles virus, mumps virus, and more. Does that mean you are
now infected? Of course not. It means you likely are immune to infection
with these viruses. That probably is the situation in Malaysia. Finding
otherwise healthy people and pigs with antibody to Nipah virus no more
means these people and pigs are infected than finding a person with
antibody to West Nile virus in New York City means that person is currently
infected. This is Microbiology 101.
Another message to ProMED-mail indicated that newspaper reports that the
virus had re-emerged rattled many Malaysians, especially the Chinese
community, which consumes pork. What we have here is a lack of
communication, and information. Alternatively, if these four healthy people
seroconverted (from no antibody in the first blood collected to antibody in
the next blood collected, that would be a different story. - Mod. CHC
...........................................jw/mp/chc/ds
